  "text": "The speci c rate of carbon xation is described as an increasing function of Q and D p , which allows a generic analysis of the model [CITATION_1] . Depending on the choice for D p , four di erent models are obtained, based on three di erent hypotheses on the mechanisms driving both photosynthesis and calci cation. The models have been calibrated in order to predict the same carbon uxes in nowadays pCO 2 , on the basis on available experimental results [CITATION_2] . Parameter values are presented in Table 1 and Table 2 .",
